description: From Latin circumductus, past participle of circumducere (“to lead around”), from circum + ducere (“to lead”).

verbs.description: circumduct (third-person singular simple present circumducts, present participle circumducting, simple past and past participle circumducted)

entries.meaning: (anatomy) To move an extremity about an axis so that the distal end delineates a circle whilst the proximal end stays fixed.

examples: But Acts of Judicature may be cancelled and circumducted by the Will and Direction of the Judge

entries.meaning: (law) Alternative form of circumduce (“to close a case to further proof”)
